ce:section.ce:para:
The surface-charge of the M@CDs was analyzed by zeta potential and related with that of the pristine CDs. Samples for Zeta potential measurement were prepared by mixing 5 mL of water with 0.5 mL of M@CDs suspension. Fig. 3
                         presents the zeta potential curves of the CDs with and without doping, indicating that the zeta potentials of the CDs, Ag@CDs and Au@CDs are negative, while the other samples, namely Ga@CDs, Sn@CDs, and Zn@CDs revealed positive zeta potentials, which increased (i.e., became more as they seem quite obvious) with increasing Ga content (see Table 1
                        ). The positive zeta potentials prove that metallic Ga or Ga+3, Sn or Sn+4, and Zn or Zn+2 ions reside within these dots, specifically on or near the surface; the dots are around 10 nm in diameter, so any site is necessarily near the surface of the dot. The Ag@CDs and Au@CDs show negative zeta potentials, possibly due to the presence on the surface of the dots of small amounts of Ag and Au ions, respectively.
